---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Ionic bonds explained" description="Learn what ionic bonds are, how they form, and why table salt is a perfect example">
  <style>
    .article-header { background: #085041; border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .tags { display: flex; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .tag { font-size: 11px; padding: 3px 10px; border-radius: 999px; font-weight: 500; }
    .article-title { font-size: 28px; font-weight: 600; color: #E1F5EE; line-height: 1.3; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .objective { background: #0F6E56; border-radius: 8px; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; font-size: 14px; color: #E1F5EE; }
    .objective strong { color: #FAC775; }
    .vocab-box { background: #E1F5EE; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .vocab-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: #085041; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; margin-bottom: 12px; }
    .vocab-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr)); gap: 10px; }
    .vocab-item { background: white; border-radius: 8px; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; }
    .vocab-word { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: #085041; margin-bottom: 3px; }
    .vocab-def { font-size: 13px; color: #555; line-height: 1.5; }
    .video-wrapper { background: #1a1a2e; border-radius: 12px; aspect-ratio: 16/9; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; overflow: hidden; }
    .video-wrapper iframe { width: 100%; height: 100%; border: none; }
    .video-caption { font-size: 13px; color: #888; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .facts-box { background: #f5f5f5; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .facts-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: #085041; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; margin-bottom: 12px; }
    .fact { display: flex; gap: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; align-items: flex-start; }
    .fact-dot { width: 8px; height: 8px; border-radius: 50%; background: #085041; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 6px; }
    .fact-text { font-size: 15px; color: #1a1a2e; line-height: 1.6; }
    .fact-text strong { color: #085041; }
    .summary-box { background: #085041; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .summary-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: #FAC775; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .summary-text { font-size: 15px; color: #E1F5EE; line-height: 1.7; }
    .topic-tags { display: flex; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2rem; }
    .topic-tag { font-size: 12px; padding: 5px 12px; border-radius: 999px; }
  </style>

  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#412402;">General</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Bonding</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">Ionic bonds explained</h1>
    <div class="objective"><strong>Learning objective:</strong> Explain how ionic bonds form and give an example of an ionic compound.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-box">
    <div class="vocab-title">Key vocabulary</div>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Ionic bond</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A bond formed when one atom transfers electrons to another, creating oppositely charged ions that attract each other.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Ion</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">An atom that has gained or lost electrons and now has a positive or negative charge.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Cation</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A positively charged ion. Formed when an atom loses electrons.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Anion</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A negatively charged ion. Formed when an atom gains electrons.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Octet rule</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">Atoms are most stable when they have 8 electrons in their outer shell.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Lattice</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A regular repeating structure of ions held together by ionic bonds.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="video-wrapper">
    <iframe
      src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/CGA8sRwqIFg"
      title="Ionic Bonding — Tyler DeWitt"
      allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
      allowfullscreen>
    </iframe>
  </div>
  <p class="video-caption">Tyler DeWitt explains ionic bonding with clear examples — great for beginners and general chemistry students.</p>

  <div class="facts-box">
    <div class="facts-title">Key facts</div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">Ionic bonds form between a <strong>metal</strong> and a <strong>non-metal</strong>. The metal loses electrons and the non-metal gains them.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">When sodium (Na) gives one electron to chlorine (Cl), sodium becomes <strong>Na⁺</strong> and chlorine becomes <strong>Cl⁻</strong>. Opposite charges attract — this is the ionic bond.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">Atoms transfer electrons to achieve a <strong>full outer shell</strong> of 8 electrons. This is called the octet rule and makes atoms more stable.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">Ionic compounds form a <strong>crystal lattice</strong> — a giant repeating structure of positive and negative ions. This makes them hard solids with high melting points.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">Ionic compounds <strong>conduct electricity</strong> when dissolved in water or melted because the ions are free to move and carry charge.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="summary-box">
    <div class="summary-title">Summary</div>
    <div class="summary-text">
      Ionic bonds form when a metal atom transfers electrons to a non-metal atom, creating positive and negative ions that attract each other. Both atoms achieve a full outer shell of electrons making them more stable. Ionic compounds form hard crystal lattices and conduct electricity when dissolved in water.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-tags">
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Bonding</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#633806;">General</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#534AB7;">Ionic bonds</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E6F1FB;color:#0C447C;">Octet rule</span>
  </div>
</Layout>